Short Explanation of the Problem

Your User Page Controller is probably loading posts like this:

$posts = Post::all();

This loads posts but does not explicitly load the category relationship, so sometimes the old category data remains cached in the query.

Step-by-Step Fix
Step 1 — Load Category Relationship Properly

Open your HomeController

app/Http/Controllers/HomeController.php

Change this:

$posts = Post::all();

to

$posts = Post::with('category')->get();

Full example:

public function index()
{
    $posts = Post::with('category')->get();

    return view('user.home', compact('posts'));
}

This ensures latest category data is always fetched from the database.

Step 2 — Verify Category Relationship

Open:

app/Models/Post.php

Make sure this exists:

public function category()
{
    return $this->belongsTo(Category::class);
}
Step 3 — Check User Interface Blade

Open:

resources/views/user/home.blade.php

Example correct usage:

@foreach($posts as $post)

<h2>{{ $post->title }}</h2>

<p>{{ $post->content }}</p>

<p>Category: {{ $post->category->name }}</p>

<p>{{ $post->category->description }}</p>

@endforeach

Now when category description changes → frontend updates automatically.

Step 4 — Clear Laravel Cache (Important)

Run these commands once:

php artisan cache:clear
php artisan config:clear
php artisan view:clear
Step 5 — Refresh Browser Hard

Press:

CTRL + SHIFT + R

This clears browser cache.

Correct Data Flow
Category Table
      ↓
Post belongsTo Category
      ↓
Controller loads Post + Category
      ↓
Blade shows latest category description
